Guidelines for the Use of Al in Candidate
Assessments

(With Human-in-the-Loop Evaluation)

Purpose

Our assessment process reflects modern professional environments where Al-assisted
tools are increasingly part of everyday work. These guidelines establish clear
expectations for how candidates may use Al tools during assessments and how Al may
used as part of the evaluation process.

The intent is to evaluate a candidate's thinking, judgment, problem-solving approach,
and accountability, rather than their ability to avoid or overuse Al.

Candidate Use of Al Tools

Candidates may use Al tools during assessments, provided the use aligns with the
principles below.

Acceptable Uses

Al may be used to:

. Brainstorm ideas or generate initial outlines
. Clarify concepts, terminology, or frameworks
. Explore alternative solutions or approaches
. Generate, review, or refactor example code
. Identify trade-offs, risks, or edge cases
. Improve clarity, organization, or readability of written responses

Unacceptable Uses

Al may not be used to:

Transparency Expectations

We value professional transparency and integrity.

. Candidates are not required to disclose detailed prompts, tools, or workflows.
. Candidates may optionally include a brief statement acknowledging Al use (e.g
"Al tools were used to explore options and refine clarity; all conclusions are my
own. ”)

Transparency may be used to provide context, and it does not elicit a scoring penalty.

