What We Evaluate

Assessments are evaluated on the quality of thinking and decision-making, not on
stylistic polish or Al usage alone.

Evaluation criteria commonly include:

. Problem framing and assumptions
. Depth of reasoning and systems thinking
. Trade-off analysis and prioritization
Technical or domain understanding (where applicable)
. Clarity and structure of communication
. Ownership, accountability, and judgment

Submissions that are overly generic, templated, or lacking a clear point of view may be
evaluated less favorably than concise, opinionated, and well-reasoned responses.

Use of Al in Evaluation (Human-in-the-Loop)

Al may be used to support the evaluation process, always with human oversight.

Al May Assist With:

. Identifying patterns across submissions
. Highlighting areas for deeper human review
. Supporting consistency and calibration
· Flagging boilerplate or low-signal responses

Al Is Not Used To:

. Make final hiring or advancement decisions
. Automatically score or rank candidates
. Replace human reviewers or panel discussions
. Penalize candidates solely for Al usage

All final evaluations and decisions are made by human reviewers.

Principles That Guide This Approach

. Responsible Al use is expected, not discouraged
. Original thinking and accountability matter most
. Human judgment remains central to evaluation
. Transparency builds trust in the process

Final Guidance to Candidates

These assessments reflect real-world professional expectations:

. Use Al as a tool, not a substitute
. Apply judgment, context, and experience
. Take ownership of all outputs
. Be prepared to explain and defend your thinking
